vz64 kernel bringup notes
=========================

Platform: 9front kernel running as guest under Apple Virtualization.framework
Guest starts at EL1 (hypervisor at EL2).  Host-side runner: 9vz (mac).

SMP: DONE -- 2-cpu boot verified
--------------------------------
A 2-cpu guest (9vz default -cpus 2, *ncpu unset) boots cleanly to
the interactive rc prompt with cpu1 online.  cpu0 brings cpu1 up
via PSCI CPU_ON (SMC64 0xC4000003); cpu1 runs the secondary path
(trapinit/fpuinit/intrinit/clockinit/synccycles/timersinit/
mmu1init/schedinit) and joins the scheduler.  The whole bug chain
that got us here (Bugs 1-7g below) is preserved as the historical
record; the decisive ones for SMP were:
  - PSCI CPU_ON needs the SMC64 id (Bug 7g block / mpinit).
  - getrregs cannot match by GICR_TYPER affinity under VZ (TYPER
    reads all-zero); it falls back to POSITIONAL indexing, cpu N
    = Nth 0x20000 redistributor frame, bounded by the DTB region
    (Bug 7g, gic.c).
  - GICR_WAKER must be cleared on the secondary before its SGI/PPI
    frame responds (Bug 7c, intrinit).
  - main.c BSS clear gated on cpu0; uartvz TX serialised with the
    vcon.txl ilock so two cpus printing do not corrupt the vring.

Apple Virtualization CPU count: NOT limited to two.  We tested 2
because 9vz defaults to -cpus 2 and that was the next unverified
step; the count comes from VZVirtualMachineConfiguration.cpuCount,
whose ceiling is min(host performance-core count, a framework max)
-- reported by VZVirtualMachineConfiguration.maximumAllowedCPUCount
at runtime (typically the number of physical cores on the host).
Our path has no 2-cpu assumption: conf.nmach comes from the DTB
cpu nodes / *ncpu, the redistributor walk and cpumpid[] are sized
by MAXMACH, and getrregs indexes by machno.  To try more cpus:
launch 9vz with -cpus N (N <= maximumAllowedCPUCount) and leave
*ncpu unset.  If a higher count misbehaves, set *gicdebug and
*smpdebug (below) and read the per-cpu redistributor map +
heartbeat.

SMP diagnostics (now gated, quiet by default)
---------------------------------------------
The bring-up instrumentation is kept but silenced so a normal boot
is clean.  Re-enable from the kernel config / cmdline:
  *gicdebug   gic.c   dumprregs() the redistributor map in cpu0
                      intrinit; bootargs.c prints the captured GIC
                      node + gicd/gicr base/size + per-cpu stride.
  *smpdebug   main.c  mpinit prints each PSCI CPU_ON target, and
                      the secondary prints a per-stage heartbeat
                      ("cpuN main: <stage>") so a silent wedge names
                      the stage that hung.
dumprregs() is also still called automatically right before the
getrregs panic, and synccycles() still announces a stuck barrier
("synccycles: cpuN stuck ... have M of K"), regardless of the
switches -- those only fire on failure.  cpuidprint() still prints
"cpuN: Apple Virtualization.framework" per cpu, so a healthy boot
confirms every secondary online without any debug switch.

Native GUI: IN PROGRESS -- host window opens, guest drivers TODO
----------------------------------------------------------------
The plan is a native graphics path so a 9front guest runs rio in a
real macOS window (not just drawterm).  Work is split host/guest;
the host half is the 9vz launcher (mac), the guest half is driver
work in this kernel.  Launch with 9vz -gui (adds a virtio-gpu
device with one scanout, a USB keyboard, and a USB absolute-coord
pointing device; serial still flows on stdio).

GUI Bug 1: -gui crashed on the HOST before the window opened (FIXED)
  Symptom: a full, clean guest boot (all cpus to schedinit, "state:
  running"), then the 9vz process itself crashed on the mac side:
      SIGTRAP: trace trap
      signal arrived during cgo execution
      ...startVirtualMachineWindow...
      ...(*VirtualMachine).StartGraphicApplication...
      ...main.main (main.go:197)
  i.e. NOT a kernel fault -- the guest was fine; the host launcher
  trapped inside AppKit as it tried to create the window.
  ROOT CAUSE (host, 9vz/main.go): AppKit ([NSApplication
  sharedApplication] / [NSApp run], reached via vz's
  StartGraphicApplication -> startVirtualMachineWindow) MUST run on
  the process's main OS thread (the startup thread, m0).  main.go
  called runtime.LockOSThread() inside main(), right before
  StartGraphicApplication -- too late: by then the Go scheduler had
  migrated goroutine 1 onto another M, so the lock pinned AppKit to
  a NON-main thread and AppKit aborted via a brk (-> SIGTRAP).  The
  crash dump confirmed it: "goroutine 1 ... m=4 ... locked to
  thread" -- m=4, not m0; and register r6 spelled "ispatch" (a
  libdispatch/main-thread assertion).
  FIX (host, 9vz/main.go): move runtime.LockOSThread() into an
  init() function.  init and main.main both run on goroutine 1,
  which starts life on the process main/startup thread; locking in
  init() pins it there before the scheduler can move it, so AppKit
  ends up on the thread it requires.  Removed the now-redundant
  LockOSThread() in the -gui branch.  Headless boots unaffected
  (the lock just stays held, harmless).
  This bug is entirely host-side; no vz64 kernel change.  The fix
  lives in the 9vz repo (mac), not here.  Recorded here because the
  crash LOOKED like it might be ours (it followed a kernel boot)
  and the next GUI bugs WILL be ours.

  STATUS after the fix: window should open (titled "9vz") but paint
  BLACK -- expected.  The guest-side virtio-gpu/keyboard/mouse
  drivers below are not written yet, so nothing drives the scanout.
  [SUPERSEDED: the virtio-gpu driver IS now written (screen.c) and
  gets through the handshake + GET_DISPLAY_INFO; it stalled at
  RESOURCE_CREATE_2D (GUI Bug 2, format-probe fix), then -- with
  create-2d passing -- at RESOURCE_ATTACH_BACKING, which a bogus
  size guard failed SILENTLY (GUI Bug 3, fix applied).  With Bug 3
  fixed the scanout setup should complete and the window paint.
  Latest -gui boot still showed a BLACK window: that boot was the
  pre-Bug-3 binary (scanout setup failed at attach-backing).]

GUI Bug 2: RESOURCE_CREATE_2D rejected -- err-invalid-parameter (FIX APPLIED)
  Symptom: the virtio-gpu driver (screen.c) now does the virtio 1.0
  handshake, brings up the control queue, and the FIRST control-
  queue round trip succeeds:
      virtio-gpu: PCI.0.8.0 did 0x1050 rid 1
      virtio-gpu: scanout0 1024x768 enabled=1
  i.e. GET_DISPLAY_INFO works (queue, descriptors, notify, used-ring
  poll, response parse all correct, and the host reports a live
  1024x768 scanout).  The very next command, RESOURCE_CREATE_2D,
  fails:
      virtio-gpu: create-2d: err-invalid-parameter (0x1205)
      virtio-gpu: scanout setup failed
  DIAGNOSIS: by the virtio-gpu spec the parameters were all valid
  (resource_id 1 != 0, width 1024, height 768, format
  B8G8R8A8_UNORM = 1).  A QEMU/Linux host accepts exactly that.  But
  err-invalid-parameter from CREATE_2D means a field was rejected,
  and since geometry and resource_id are fine, the suspect is the
  pixel FORMAT: Apple Virtualization.framework's virtio-gpu
  whitelists a narrower set of virtio_gpu_formats than QEMU, and the
  one we hardcoded is evidently not on it.  (GET_DISPLAY_INFO does
  not name a format, which is why it sailed through and create-2d is
  the first command to exercise the whitelist.)
  FIX (screen.c): stop hardcoding the format.  gpucreate2d() now
  PROBES a candidate list (gpufmts[], B8G8R8X8/B8G8R8A8/X8R8G8B8/...
  most-likely-first for an XRGB32 [B,G,R,X]-in-memory framebuffer),
  retrying RESOURCE_CREATE_2D down the list and accepting the first
  format the host does NOT reject with err-invalid-parameter.  The
  chosen format is remembered in gpufmt.  Retry is safe because a
  CREATE_2D that returns invalid-parameter does not create the
  resource, so resource_id 1 is still free for the next attempt.
  Any NON-invalid-parameter error (out-of-memory, etc.) breaks out
  immediately and is printed -- so if the real cause turns out NOT
  to be the format, the next boot says so instead of silently
  burning through all 8 candidates.  A successful non-default format
  is announced ("host accepted format %#ux (not %#ux)") so we learn
  which format VZ actually wants and can promote it to the head of
  the list (or hardcode it) later.
  UNTESTED -- compiles clean (mk in /sys/src/9/vz64).  Next boot
  with 9vz -gui: read the create-2d line.
    - "host accepted format 0xN" => fixed; note N, expect the boot
      to proceed to attach-backing / set-scanout (the next two
      candidates for an err- line).
    - "host rejected all 8 formats" => the problem is NOT the format
      whitelist after all; re-examine the CREATE_2D struct layout
      (Gpucreate2d: hdr 24 + resid/format/width/height) or whether
      VZ wants a 3D/virgl context first.
    - a different err- name printed => that error (not invalid-
      parameter) is the real blocker; chase it directly.

