GUI Bug 3b: spec-driven lifecycle tracing added (THIS SESSION)
  A second opinion framed the debug the right way: classify the
  problem (2D scanout / backing / 3D-capset), use the virtio 1.3
  GPU spec as normative, compare to QEMU 2D first, and do NOT
  assume virgl/blob/hostmem unless Apple exposes host-visible blob
  resources + a hostmem window + capset negotiation + renderer
  integration.  Working through our code against that discipline:
    - PROBLEM CLASS: 2D scanout + resource backing.  Not 3D.  We
      never negotiate virgl/blob/context-init, so capset
      negotiation is irrelevant -- correctly so.
    - FEATURES: we accept ONLY VIRTIO_F_VERSION_1 (word1 bit0) and
      drive feature WORD 0 entirely to zero.  Word 0 is where the
      virtio-gpu options live (VIRGL=0 EDID=1 RESOURCE_UUID=2
      RESOURCE_BLOB=3 CONTEXT_INIT=4); zeroing it keeps us on the
      plain 2D path QEMU implements.  This already satisfies the
      "do not assume virgl/blob/hostmem" caution -- no code change
      needed there, it was a confirmation not a fix.
    - 64-bit queue-register writes (vout64) are a single aligned
      MMIO store; virtio-net and virtio-blk use the identical path
      under VZ and work, so the queue setup is not the divergence.
    - FIRST DIVERGENCE on the last boot was attach-backing, and it
      was OUR bug (the bogus 1KB size guard, GUI Bug 3), not a host
      behaviour difference.
  So the second opinion did not point at a new root cause -- but it
  correctly insisted we stop INFERRING the lifecycle and TRACE it.
  Instrumentation added this session (screen.c, compiles clean):
    - gpuprobe: reads and PRINTS both offered feature words and the
      driver-accepted bits:
        virtio-gpu: devfeat <w1>:<w0> drvfeat <w1>:<w0>
      so the next boot shows outright whether VZ even offers virgl/
      blob (expected: it does not / we take none).
    - gpucreate2d: now ALWAYS prints the accepted format and which
      candidate index it was (was silent for the default format):
        virtio-gpu: create-2d: ok, host accepted format 0xN
                    (candidate K of 8)
    - screeninit: a per-step transcript -- a "setup WxHx32 fb ..."
      line, then explicit ok/failed markers after create-2d,
      attach-backing, and set-scanout, and distinct
        scanout setup failed at <create-2d|attach-backing|set-scanout>
      messages so the failing COMMAND is named (no more bare
      "scanout setup failed").
    - screeninit: brackets the first flush --
        virtio-gpu: control path up; painting console banner
        virtio-gpu: first flush issued; window should paint now
      so a black window WITH all-ok control lines localises the bug
      to the TRANSFER_TO_HOST_2D/RESOURCE_FLUSH data path (offset/
      stride/rect) rather than resource setup.
  NET: behaviour unchanged except for prints; the next -gui boot is
  now self-describing.  Read the transcript top to bottom; the last
  "ok" line names the last command the host accepted, and the
  "first flush issued" line vs a black window separates control-path
  from data-path bugs.

GUI Bug 4: -gui throttled file I/O by orders of magnitude (FIX APPLIED)
  Symptom (the human, running with a serial console only): booting
  with 9vz -gui sent guest LOAD way up and dropped file-system
  performance by SEVERAL ORDERS OF MAGNITUDE versus a headless
  boot.  Open question last session was whether 9vz was spamming
  the kernel or the driver was to blame.  It is the driver.

  ROOT CAUSE (screen.c, the virtio-gpu flush path).  flushmemscreen
  drove the control queue SYNCHRONOUSLY with interrupts DISABLED:
      ilock(&vgpu);                 // splhi -- interrupts OFF
      gputransfer(...);             // notify + busy-spin on used ring
      gpuflush(...);                // notify + busy-spin on used ring
      iunlock(&vgpu);
  and ctlcmd's wait was a bare
      while(q->used->idx == q->lastused) coherence();
  So EVERY flushmemscreen:
    (a) held splhi across TWO full host round trips.  VZ's virtio
        backend is a concurrent host thread, so each round trip is
        a notify (VM exit) plus host scheduling latency -- and for
        that whole window the guest could take NO interrupts: not
        the virtual timer, and crucially NOT the virtio-blk
        completion interrupt.  The root filesystem runs over
        virtio-blk, so its I/O completions were stalled behind a
        storm of flushes.  With *ncpu=1 there was no other cpu to
        make progress either.  That is the orders-of-magnitude
        slowdown.
    (b) BUSY-WAITED (spun) instead of yielding, so the cpu burned
        100% during every flush -> the load spike.
  And devdraw calls flushmemscreen for every dirty rectangle, so
  rio (cursor blink, text, window ops) produced a continuous flush
  storm.  Headless boots were unaffected because the driver is
  dormant with no GPU device -- exactly the prediction in the
  "GUI Bug 2 -- WHAT TO CAPTURE" note ("the suspect is the
  synchronous per-character flushmemscreen (ilock + polled
  transfer+flush)").

  FIX (screen.c):
    1. Wait for completion by SLEEPING on the control-queue
       interrupt instead of busy-spinning with interrupts off.
       initqueue now leaves the queue interrupt ENABLED (no
       Rnointerrupt); gpuprobe wires intrenable(...interrupt...)
       and sets vgpu.intr.  A new interrupt() handler acks the ISR
       and wakeup()s the queue Rendez (same shape as
       ethervirtio10.c).  ctlwait()/the gpuxferflush wait loop
       tsleep on a predicate (ctlhasroom).  tsleep (5ms), not
       sleep, is a safety net: if VZ ever fails to deliver the
       used-ring interrupt, the timeout re-polls and we still make
       progress rather than hang.  cansleep() gates the sleep on
       vgpu.intr && up!=nil && islo() so the early screeninit
       bring-up (up==nil, before schedinit) and any !islo() console
       path fall back to polling -- but polling now WITHOUT forcing
       interrupts off.
    2. Replace ilock(&vgpu) on the flush path with a QLock
       (vgpu.ctll), so the wait runs at spllo with interrupts on.
       A small ilock (vgpu.il) still covers just the brief vring
       index/descriptor update the interrupt handler also reads.
    3. Coalesce the per-flush TRANSFER_TO_HOST_2D + RESOURCE_FLUSH
       into gpuxferflush(): post BOTH commands' avail entries, then
       notify ONCE and wait for BOTH completions in one wait spell.
       Halves the notifies/wakeups per flush.
  screeninit's ilock/iunlock wrappers around the bring-up commands
  were removed (single-threaded boot, up==nil so qlock would panic;
  ctlcmd's internal vgpu.il is the only exclusion needed there).
  The now-unused gputransfer()/gpuflush() helpers were deleted.

  NET: interrupts are never forced off across a host round trip,
  the cpu yields while waiting, and there is one round trip per
  flush instead of two.  File I/O under -gui should no longer be
  starved by drawing, and the load spike should disappear.

  UNTESTED -- compiles clean (mk in /sys/src/9/vz64; 9vz.bin
  regenerated).  WHAT TO CAPTURE on the next -gui boot:
    - confirm the window still paints (the bring-up path now polls
      rather than spins, but the command sequence is unchanged).
    - run a file-I/O workload in the guest with the GUI active
      (e.g. a big cp / tar / dd to the hjfs root) and compare
      throughput + load (cat /dev/sysstat, or just feel) against a
      headless boot.  Expectation: comparable now.
    - if it STILL feels slow under -gui: the next suspect is the
      flush GRANULARITY (one host round trip per dirty rect is
      still a lot when rio scribbles).  The follow-on optimisation
      would be to COALESCE/THROTTLE flushes -- accumulate dirty
      rects and flush at a bounded rate (e.g. on a timer) rather
      than one round trip per devdraw operation -- but that is only
      worth doing if the interrupt-off fix alone is not enough.
    - if the window goes BLACK or the guest wedges on first flush:
      suspect the used-ring interrupt is not being delivered for
      the GPU device (then ctlhasroom never becomes true via
      interrupt and we rely on the 5ms tsleep timeout).  The boot
      would still progress (timeout path) but slowly; say so and we
      either fix the intr wiring (p->intl / tbdf for the GPU) or
      shorten/remove the sleep in favour of a tuned poll.

GUI guest-side work, NOT STARTED (this is the kernel's half):
  1. virtio-gpu driver doing the virtio 1.0 handshake (crib the
     ring/feature-negotiation structure from uartvz.c), then the
     control queue: GET_DISPLAY_INFO, RESOURCE_CREATE_2D,
     RESOURCE_ATTACH_BACKING (point at the Plan 9 framebuffer
     pages), SET_SCANOUT, and TRANSFER_TO_HOST_2D + RESOURCE_FLUSH
     on update.
  2. hook that into the soft-framebuffer screen path so
     flushmemscreen issues the transfer/flush for the dirty
     rectangle the draw layer already tracks.
  3. USB-HID input drivers feeding /dev/kbd and /dev/mouse from the
     VZ keyboard and pointing devices.
  Suggested first proof (host path, zero kernel work): boot a stock
  Linux arm64 kernel under 9vz -gui; if a Linux console paints in
  the window, the whole host path (virtio-gpu + window + input) is
  proven good and only the guest driver remains.

GOTCHA noted by the human (testing logistics): the disk image
cannot be shared across concurrent runs, so a -gui boot and a
headless boot of the same 9front.raw cannot run at the same time.
Stop one before starting the other (and fshalt the guest first --
hjfs buffers writes).

Build / image workflow
----------------------
The linker output 9vz goes through aux/aout2uimage producing 9vz.u
(64-byte uImage header + text + data).  The mkfile then strips that
header to produce 9vz.bin (target $p$CONF.bin -- the dd that used
to be a manual mac-side step is now part of `mk`).  On the mac side
just boot the .bin directly, no header tools:

  ./9vz -kernel 9vz.bin ...               # boot it directly

(Historically this was done by hand:
  dd if=9vz.u of=9vz.bin bs=64 skip=1     # now done by the mkfile)

l.s now embeds an ARM64 Linux-style boot header at _start:
  code0 = B _hdrend (jumps over the 64-byte header)
  text_offset = 0x100000  (image loads at RAM base + 0x100000 = KTZERO)
  image_size  = 32MB
  flags       = 0x2 (LE, 4K pages, image near RAM base)
  magic       = "ARM\x64" at offset 56

IMPORTANT: do NOT also run mkarm64hdr.py on the new binary.  That
tool prepends a second header with text_offset=0xfffc0 (it assumed
the header was NOT part of the linked text).  The two schemes must
not be mixed.  The python tool was the old workaround; the embedded
header replaces it.

GOTCHA (bit us once): mkarm64hdr.py detects the embedded header
(magic at offset 56) and exits WITHOUT writing the output file.
If you keep step 3 in the build script, step 4 silently boots a
STALE 9vz.img from a previous build.  Boot 9vz.bin directly:
  ./9vz -kernel 9vz.bin -disk ... -cmdline '...'

ROOT CAUSE of the long "data segment garbage" hunt (was Bug 2):
the image was being loaded at the wrong offset.  The old python
header pass put the text at a 64-byte offset from where the linker
expected it (text_offset mismatch).  Every symbol ended up reading
memory 64 bytes off (or worse), which presented as "static
variables contain garbage".  fmtlclear() "worked" only because it
zeroed whatever was at the (shifted) &fmtl.  Bulk-zeroing
bdata..end "didn't work" because it wiped shifted initialized data
and crashed.  None of l.s was ever corrupting anything -- skipping
every physical-address op changed nothing because the corruption
was a load-time layout problem.

With the header fixed: quotefmtinstall and bootargsinit pass
without any zeroing hacks.  (fmtlclear may now be unnecessary --
UNTESTED, try removing it once boot gets further.)

Bug 1: LDXR/STXR livelock (FIXED)
----------------------------------
Apple VZ clears the exclusive monitor on guest exits, so LDXR/STXR
loops in tas() and cmpswap() can livelock.  Replaced with ARMv8.1
LSE atomics in l.s:
  tas:     SWPW  (WORD $0xB8218000)
  cmpswap: CASW  (WORD $0x88A17C02)
All Apple Silicon supports LSE.

Bug 2: image load offset (FIXED -- see workflow above)
-------------------------------------------------------
Historical test results from this hunt, kept for reference:
  - Plan 9 7l places static uninitialized vars < MINSIZ (64 bytes)
    in the DATA segment, not BSS (dodata pass 1 promotes small
    SBSS to SDATA).  True, but was a red herring.
  - fmtlwhere() confirmed &fmtl < edata (in data segment).
  - The l.s physical-address ops (mmudisable, cache flushes,
    _zerol1, _zerobss, mmuidmap, mmu0init) were each/all skipped
    with no change -- they were never the problem.

Bug 4: embedded header scrambled by linker (FIX APPLIED)
---------------------------------------------------------
First attempt at the embedded header used "B _hdrend(SB)" as
code0.  check_kernel.sh showed garbage at offset 56 instead of the
magic: 7l's follow()/xfol pass chases unconditional branches and
lays the target code at offset 0, scattering the header WORDs.
Linked addresses stay self-consistent, but the file no longer
starts with the header, so VZ rejects it ("failed to start").

Fix: encode code0 as WORD $0x14000010 (b .+64) so the linker sees
only data, never a branch to chase.  Same trick mkarm64hdr.py uses.

Until the embedded header is verified by check_kernel.sh, the
python-tool path (text_offset 0xfffc0 on a plain binary) still
works and was used to verify meminit below.

Bug 3: meminit hang (FIXED, VERIFIED)
--------------------------------------
mmu0init maps all 2GB of VDRAM with 2MB PTEBLOCK entries.  Later
meminit->kmapram->l1map walks the same range and hit
  assert((l1[PTL1X(va,1)] & PTETABLE) == PTETABLE)
on those PTEBLOCK entries.  assert -> panic -> print before
printinit = silent hang.

Fix in mmu.c l1map(): if an L1 entry is already a valid PTEBLOCK,
skip forward to the next 2MB boundary instead of asserting.  The
mmu0init mapping attributes (kernel RW, inner-share, WB cache) are
fine for RAM, so skipping is correct.

VERIFIED: meminit fix works (vzstop after meminit fired cleanly).
VERIFIED: embedded header works -- check_kernel.sh validates
9vz.bin and VZ boots it directly, no python step.
VERIFIED: confinit, xinit, printinit, print all pass (vzstop after
print fired cleanly).

Full boot attempt HUNG somewhere in: trapinit, fpuinit, intrinit,
clockinit, cpuidprint, timersinit, pageinit, procinit0, initseg,
links, chandevreset, userinit, mpinit, mmu1init, schedinit.

PRIME SUSPECT: clockinit writes PMU registers (PMCR_EL0,
PMCNTENSET, PMUSERENR_EL0).  Apple VZ does not give guests a PMU;
those syswr()s likely take an undefined-instruction trap.  Vectors
are installed by then (trapinit ran), so it probably panics into
the invisible buffered console.  Related: lcycles() reads
PMCCNTR_EL0 -- same problem whenever something calls it.

VERIFIED: trapinit, fpuinit, intrinit all pass (probe between
intrinit and clockinit stopped cleanly).  The GIC works under VZ.

Bug 5: PMU registers unimplemented under VZ (FIX APPLIED)
----------------------------------------------------------
clockinit wrote PMCR_EL0/PMCNTENSET/PMUSERENR_EL0; Apple VZ guests
have no PMU, so those syswr()s trap (vectors installed by then ->
panic into invisible buffered console -> silent hang).  The PMU
was vestigial anyway: cycles() uses vcycles()/CNTVCT_EL0.
  - clock.c: PMU writes commented out.
  - l.s: lcycles() now reads CNTVCT_EL0 instead of PMCCNTR_EL0.
(Untested as the hang cause -- we fixed it on suspicion and moved
the probe past it; if the next round hangs, the remaining parts of
clockinit are still candidates: CNTV_TVAL/CTL writes, CNTKCTL,
intrenable(IRQcntvns).)

VERIFIED: clockinit (de-PMU'd), cpuidprint, timersinit, pageinit,
procinit0, initseg, links ALL PASS.  Virtio console is UP: PCI
enumeration messages appeared on the host terminal before the
clean vzstop.  Bisection era over -- failures should now print.

Bug 6: uartvz txwait did not wait (FIX APPLIED)
------------------------------------------------
txwait() was:
    while(q->lastused != q->used->idx)
        q->lastused++;
i.e. lastused = used->idx -- a no-op that never waits for the
DEVICE.  putc/kick/ringflush all do txpost(); txwait(); and then
reuse the same descriptor + buffer for the next chunk.  The VZ
console backend is asynchronous: stale avail entries pointing at
a rewritten descriptor/buffer get processed late, emitting
duplicated/interleaved text, and a sufficiently confused ring
wedges TX entirely.

Observed symptoms, all from this one bug:
  - whole PCI message block printed twice (sequential dup)
  - chandevreset's ether probe line with every char ~doubled
    ("110000MMbbpss pp oo rr tt..." = two skewed copies racing)
  - console output freezing mid-line (the "hang" -- guest may
    well still be running with a dead TX queue)

Fix: txwait now spins until used->idx == avail->idx (both
free-running u16; equal = queue idle), with coherence() as
read/compiler barrier, then syncs lastused.

VERIFIED after txwait fix: full clean boot output through
chandevreset's ether probe -- xinit hole report, "Plan 9" banner,
timer frequency, cpu0 banner, memory summary, single-copy PCI
enumeration, #l0 virtio10 1000Mbps with MAC.  The "missing early
prints" and both doubling symptoms are all gone; they were all the
txwait bug.

MILESTONE: FULL BOOT TO INTERACTIVE RC PROMPT.  hjfs root from
/dev/sdF0/fs, glenda login, % prompt on the virtio console.  The
fmtlclear removal survived (load-offset theory confirmed).  Only
wrinkle: terminal-service profile wants #i/#m (draw/mouse) which
the headless kernel lacks; first rc dies, init restarts a bare rc.
Options: guard profile / service=cpu + drawterm / someday
virtio-gpu.

Next projects, roughly in order:
  - networking smoke test (ip/ipconfig over virtio-net NAT)
  - service=cpu + auth + drawterm from the mac
  - SMP bring-up (remove *ncpu=1, then -cpus N)   [DONE -- see
    "SMP: DONE" milestone at the top of this file]
  - virtio-gpu + devdraw/devmouse for native graphics   [IN
    PROGRESS -- host -gui window opens (GUI Bug 1 fixed); guest
    virtio-gpu driver (screen.c) written: handshake + control
    queue + GET_DISPLAY_INFO work, currently blocked at
    RESOURCE_CREATE_2D (GUI Bug 2, format-probe fix applied,
    awaiting next -gui boot).  USB-HID kbd/mouse still not
    started.  See "Native GUI" milestone near the top of this
    file and the "GUI Bug 2 -- WHAT TO CAPTURE" block.]
  - console quirks: putc/kick vring race, rx-during-flush
    [the putc/kick TX race is fixed: vcon.txl ilock now wraps
    both putc and kick in uartvz.c]

CPU server + drawterm recipe
----------------------------
Networking: Apple NAT serves DHCP on its shared subnet
(typically 192.168.64.0/24); host can reach guest directly,
outside world cannot.  In guest:
    ip/ipconfig
    cat /net/ipifc/0/status     # note guest IP for drawterm
    ndb/dnsquery 9front.org ip  # if it fails: ndb/dns -r

Conversion (FQA chapter 7 flow, grounded in auth(8)/rcpu(1)):
  1. ls /dev/sdF0 -- must have an nvram partition (else disk/prep)
  2. auth/wrkey            # machine key, authid=glenda, authdom=vz
  3. /lib/ndb/local: add
         auth=vz authdom=vz
         ipnet=vznet ip=192.168.64.0 ipmask=255.255.255.0
             auth=vz
             authdom=vz
  4. host side: add service=cpu to -cmdline; reboot.
     cpurc path: no termrc (no #i/#m errors), aux/listen serves
     /rc/bin/service including tcp17019 (rcpu, dp9ik+TLS).
  5. auth/changeuser glenda    # password for drawterm logins
  6. mac: 9front drawterm (git.9front.org/plan9front/drawterm),
     drawterm -h <guest-ip> -a <guest-ip> -u glenda

Snags: missing nvram partition -> prompts every boot; cpurc may
need ip/ipconfig in cpurc.local; authdom mismatch ndb vs wrkey ->
auth/debug on guest; DHCP IP drift -> pin with ether=/ip= in ndb.

GOTCHA: on the mac, bridge100's 192.168.64.1 is the HOST/gateway
address, not the guest.  Find the guest IP with
cat /net/ipifc/0/status (guest) or arp -a | grep <guest-mac>
(mac; the MAC is in the #l0 boot banner).  Debug order:
ping guest-ip, then nc -vz guest-ip 17019 (listener exists only
on a service=cpu boot with aux/listen running), then drawterm.

WORKING: drawterm in via listen1 + factotum plaintext (cheap but
fine inside the NAT).  To persist the rig across boots, put the
commands in /cfg/$sysname/cpurc.  Run fshalt before stopping the
VM -- hjfs buffers writes.

Persistence boundary: hjfs/nvram changes live in 9front.raw; the
KERNEL does not (VZ loads 9vz.bin fresh each launch -- guest never
needs a kernel install), and the cmdline is per-launch via DTB.

SMP preparation (FIXES APPLIED, UNTESTED)
------------------------------------------
Audit of the secondary path found one catastrophic bug and one
hang risk, both fixed:
  - main.c: the BSS clear ran BEFORE the machno check, so a
    secondary entering main() would zero live BSS under the
    running system.  Now gated on m->machno == 0 (cpu0's Mach is
    zeroed by l.s; secondaries get machno from mpinit).
  - l.s: removed the SEVL/WFE park before mmuenable.  Spin-table
    legacy; with PSCI CPU_ON the tables exist before a secondary
    ever runs, and under VZ a WFE really waits while nobody SEVs.
  - mpinit: PSCI CPU_ON return value now checked and printed on
    failure (was silently hanging in synccycles).

Looks sound by inspection: PSCI entry hits the executable header
code0; MPIDR aff0 indexes Mach (mpinit constructs target mpidr to
match); per-cpu GICR/VBAR/CNTV setup inherited from the SMP arm64
port; LSE atomics are SMP-correct; shared L1BOT/L1TOP.

TESTED: boot without *ncpu=1 reached mpinit and printed
    mpinit: PSCI CPU_ON cpu1 failed: -1
-1 = PSCI NOT_SUPPORTED.  We were calling the SMC32 function id
0x84000003; CPU_ON takes a 64-bit entry point and the SMC64 id is
0xC4000003 (what Linux uses on arm64).  The argument-less PSCI
calls (SYSTEM_OFF 0x84000008, SYSTEM_RESET 0x84000009) only exist
as SMC32 and have worked all along, which fits: Apple implements
exactly the spec'd ids, QEMU is lenient about the 32-bit CPU_ON.
FIX APPLIED in mpinit (0xC4000003), UNTESTED.  Boot once without
*ncpu=1 when convenient; the failure print makes the outcome
unambiguous either way.  Single-cpu boots are unaffected (mpinit
loop body never runs with conf.nmach == 1).
Bug 7: getrregs matched redistributor by processor number (FIX APPLIED)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
With PSCI CPU_ON fixed to the SMC64 id 0xC4000003, cpu1 now
actually starts and runs far enough to call intrinit ->
getrregs(1), where it panicked:
    panic: getrregs: no re-distributor for cpu 1
getrregs walked the GICv3 redistributor frames and matched
GICR_TYPER[23:8] (the "Processor_Number" field) against machno.
That happened to work for cpu0 but Apple VZ does not number the
redistributors 0..N to match our machno, so cpu1's search ran off
the Last redistributor and panicked.

Fix in gic.c: match by MPIDR affinity instead.  GICv3 identifies a
redistributor by the affinity value in GICR_TYPER[63:32] (the high
32-bit word, read as rregs[GICR_TYPER+1]).  getrregs is only ever
called for the currently-running cpu, so it now compares against
mpidraff(sysrd(MPIDR_EL1)) -- this cpu's own MPIDR packed into the
GIC's Aff3<<24|Aff2<<16|Aff1<<8|Aff0 layout.  No dependence on DTB
cpu-node ordering.  Redistributor stride stays 0x20000 (RD+SGI,
two 64KB frames; cpu0 worked with it so VLPIs are off).  UNTESTED
on hardware -- boot without *ncpu=1 to confirm cpu1 passes
intrinit; next candidates if it hangs are clockinit/timersinit on
the secondary and the unlocked uartvz TX race below.

Bug 7b: redistributor stride wrong under GICv4/VLPI (FIX APPLIED)
-----------------------------------------------------------------
With Bug 7's affinity-match fix in place, cpu1 still panicked:
    panic: getrregs: no re-distributor for cpu 1 (aff 0x1)
The new panic message format (showing "aff 0x1") confirms the
affinity-match code is the one running, and that cpu1's own MPIDR
read returns aff0 = 1 (so Apple DOES put the cpu index in aff0,
and cpumpid[]/mpinit are targeting the right cpu -- cpu1 truly
starts and reaches intrinit).

So the affinity packing is right but the redistributor SCAN never
finds a frame whose GICR_TYPER[63:32] == 1.  Prime suspect: the
walk stride.  GICv3 redistributors are 2x 64KB frames (RD+SGI =
0x20000), but a GICv4 implementation that supports virtual LPIs
has 4 frames per redistributor (0x40000): the extra VLPI/reserved
frames.  GICR_TYPER.VLPIS (bit 1) advertises this.  If Apple VZ's
GIC reports VLPIS, cpu0's redistributor occupies 0..0x40000 and
cpu1's starts at 0x40000; stepping by a hardcoded 0x20000 lands on
cpu0's VLPI frame, whose affinity is still cpu0's (or 0), so the
match fails and we eventually hit Last and panic.

FIX in gic.c getrregs: read GICR_TYPER.VLPIS and step by 0x40000
when set, else 0x20000.  Added an iprint of the last frame's
aff/typer before the panic so the next failure (if any) is
diagnosable: it tells us the real stride, whether Last fired
early, and what affinities the frames actually carry.  UNTESTED --
boot without *ncpu=1.  If it still panics, read the iprint: if the
"last frame typer" shows VLPIS=0 then the stride theory is wrong
and the issue is elsewhere (only one redistributor exposed? GICR
window too small? affinity packed differently by Apple?).

Bug 7d: redistributor walk overshot into all-ones GIC space (FIX APPLIED)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Bug 7b's VLPI-aware stride still panicked, and the diagnostic
iprint told the real story:
    getrregs cpu1 want 0x1: last frame aff 0xffffffff typer 0xffffffff
typer 0xffffffff is not a valid GICR_TYPER -- it is the all-ones
read of an UNMAPPED-but-decoded GIC address (a GICR offset with no
register behind it).  So the walk stepped PAST cpu1's redistributor
into dead GIC space; 0xffffffff happens to have bit 4 (Last) set,
so the loop terminated and panicked.  Conclusion: the VLPIS=>0x40000
stride guess was wrong for VZ.  cpu0's TYPER reads VLPIS set, but
VZ still spaces the redistributors 0x20000 apart, so 0x40000
overshoots.

Two-part fix:
  1. gic.c getrregs: stop guessing the stride.  Walk every 0x20000
     frame (the smallest possible RD+SGI redistributor) and match
     GICR_TYPER[63:32] affinity.  In a GICv4/VLPI layout the extra
     0x20000 sub-frames simply do not carry the target affinity, so
     stepping over them is harmless; in GICv3 each 0x20000 step
     lands exactly on an RD_base.  No VLPIS branch at all.
  2. bound the walk to the redistributor region the DEVICE TREE
     advertises (the arm,gic-v3 node's `reg`, region 1), so an
     unlucky stride can never run off into all-ones space again.
     bootargs.c now parses the intc node reg into gicdbase/gicdsize
     and gicrbase/gicrsize (handles both 2/2 and 1/1 address/size
     cell layouts; VZ uses 2/2); getrregs prefers gicrbase/gicrsize
     and falls back to the compiled-in PHYSIO+0x10000 offset if the
     DTB lacked them.
The GICR_TYPER.Last bit still ends the walk early when present.
UNTESTED on hardware -- boot without *ncpu=1 to confirm cpu1 now
passes getrregs.  If the iprint reappears with a SANE typer (not
all-ones) and aff != want for every frame, then VZ packs the
redistributor affinity differently from MPIDR and mpidraff() needs
revisiting; if gicrsize came back 0, the intc node name/reg layout
differs from the assumed "intc"/"interrupt-controller" + 2/2 cells.

Bug 7c: secondary redistributor left asleep (FIX APPLIED, pre-emptive)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
While in getrregs anyway, added the GICR_WAKER wakeup that the
GICv3 spec requires before using a redistributor's SGI/PPI frame.
A cpu brought up by PSCI CPU_ON comes out of reset with
GICR_WAKER.ProcessorSleep (bit 1) set; until software clears it
and observes ChildrenAsleep (bit 2) go low, the redistributor
ignores SGI/PPI config (our PPI enables for the virtual timer
would silently do nothing -> no clock interrupts on cpu1 ->
secondary wedged in timersinit/schedinit).  cpu0 is already awake
so the clear is a no-op there.  Done in intrinit right after
getrregs, before the SGI_base register writes.  This was a latent
problem the affinity panic was hiding; fixing it now avoids a
second round-trip once the stride fix gets cpu1 past getrregs.

KNOWN RISK (NOW FIXED): uartvz TX path had no lock; concurrent
prints from two cpus could race the vring (garbled console).  Fixed
with the vcon.txl ilock around txwait/txpost in both putc and kick
(uartvz.c).  Verified clean on the 2-cpu boot -- no garbling.

Root filesystem facts:
  - sdvirtio10 viopnp letters virtio-blk disks from 'F': the
    first -disk is sdF0, NOT sdN0.  cmdline should say
    nobootprompt=local!/dev/sdF0/fs
  - /dev/sdF0/fs only exists after bootrc runs disk/fdisk +
    disk/prep on the plan9 partition inside the image.
  - to discover interactively: omit nobootprompt once; the
    bootrc prompt's bracketed default is what probing found;
    !rc gives a rescue shell.
  - the root image must contain an arm64 userland (/arm64/bin,
    /arm64/init); an amd64-only install image will mount and
    then fail to exec init.
  - SMP works now: *ncpu may be left unset (defaults to the DTB
    cpu count) and 9vz -cpus N >= 2 boots cleanly.  *ncpu=1 still
    works to force a single-cpu boot if you want to take secondary
    bring-up out of the picture while debugging something else.

See PORT.txt for the full write-up of the port.

