Bug 7e: instrumentation added for the next SMP iteration (THIS SESSION)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Bug 7d's fix (0x20000 affinity scan bounded by gicrbase/gicrsize)
was applied but NOT yet retested; the session had to be killed
before a boot.  Rather than guess at yet another stride/affinity
theory blind, this session added DIAGNOSTIC TRACING so the next
boot prints the actual GIC layout VZ presents.  No behavioural
change for single-cpu boots.

What was added (all compiles clean, `mk` in /sys/src/9/vz64):
  1. gic.c dumprregs(): walks the whole advertised redistributor
     region and prints, per 0x20000 frame:
         frame N  off <off>  aff <GICR_TYPER[63:32]>
                  typer.lo <low word>  [Last] [PLPIS] [VLPIS]
     plus a header line with m->machno, raw MPIDR_EL1, the packed
     want-affinity, base, lim, and gicrbase/gicrsize.  Stops on an
     all-ones (unmapped) frame or the Last bit.  Declared in fns.h.
     A shared rregsbase() helper now computes base/lim for both
     dumprregs() and getrregs() (single source of truth).
  2. gic.c intrinit(): calls dumprregs() ONCE on cpu0 (machno==0),
     right after the distributor is enabled -- a known-good state,
     printed before any secondary starts.  This is the reference
     map.
  3. gic.c getrregs(): now also breaks the walk explicitly on an
     all-ones frame, and calls dumprregs() right before the panic,
     so a failed cpu1 bringup leaves the same map from cpu1's view
     in the log next to the panic.
  4. main.c mpinit(): prints per secondary, before the hvccall:
         mpinit: CPU_ON cpuN mpid <X> (dtb cpumpid[N] <Y>
                 ncpumpid <Z>) entry <PADDR(_start)>
     so you can correlate the cpu you ASKED VZ to start against the
     affinity that actually shows up in the redistributor map.

HOW TO READ THE NEXT BOOT (boot without *ncpu=1, 9vz default
-cpus 2):
  A. Find the cpu0 "dumprregs:" block (printed during cpu0
     intrinit, BEFORE any "mpinit:" line).  This is the truth about
     VZ's redistributor layout while only cpu0 is online.
       - If it lists MULTIPLE frames with distinct aff values, one
         of them should have aff == the mpid mpinit targets for
         cpu1.  If so, getrregs SHOULD now find it -> likely a clean
         pass; watch downstream (clockinit/timersinit/schedinit on
         cpu1, and the unlocked uartvz TX race -> garbled console,
         ilock fix still on TODO).
       - If it lists only ONE frame ending in Last (aff 0 only),
         VZ presents offline cpus' redistributors as ABSENT until
         PSCI CPU_ON wakes them.  Then cpu1's frame should appear
         only AFTER mpinit; the bug is visibility/ordering, and the
         per-cpu dumprregs() from getrregs (on cpu1, after CPU_ON)
         is the one to read -- if cpu1's own dump now shows its
         frame, the cpu0 reference simply couldn't see it yet.
       - If gicrsize prints as 0 in the header, the DTB intc-node
         parse failed: the node name or reg cell layout differs
         from the assumed "intc"/"interrupt-controller" + 2/2
         address/size cells.  Fix bootargs.c devtreeprop().
  B. Compare the "mpinit: CPU_ON cpu1 mpid X (dtb cpumpid[1] Y...)"
     line against the affinities in the dump.
       - If mpid X does NOT equal any frame's aff, and cpu1 still
         comes up reporting MPIDR aff 0x1 (the want in the panic),
         then mpinit targeted the wrong cpu OR mpidraff() packs
         differently than the GIC reports affinity.  Cross-check
         dtb cpumpid[1] (Y) against the running aff: if Y != the
         aff cpu1 reports, the DTB cpu-node order disagrees with
         hardware MPIDRs.
       - If mpid X DOES match a frame aff but getrregs on cpu1 still
         misses, the mismatch is in how cpu1's OWN MPIDR packs vs
         how the frame stores it -- revisit mpidraff() (Aff3 shift).
  C. The getrregs panic's own "last frame aff .. typer .." line:
       - typer all-ones (0xffffffff) again => still overshooting
         into dead space; gicrsize bound did not stop it (region
         smaller than expected, or base wrong).
       - typer SANE but no aff matched => affinity packing problem
         (B above), not a stride problem.

DONE (SMP works): the noisy diagnostics are now gated, not deleted.
The dumprregs() call in cpu0 intrinit and the bootargs GIC-layout
print are behind *gicdebug; the mpinit per-cpu print and the
secondary per-stage heartbeat are behind *smpdebug.  dumprregs()
itself is kept (still auto-called right before the getrregs panic).
See the "SMP diagnostics" block at the top of this file.

Bug 7g: affinity match is IMPOSSIBLE under VZ -- TYPER reads all-zero (FIX APPLIED)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
THE DIAGNOSTIC TRACING FROM 7e/7f PAID OFF.  A real boot without
*ncpu=1 produced the actual redistributor map and the panic, and
they settle the question the 7/7b/7d theories kept circling:

    dumprregs: cpu0 mpidr 0x80000000 want-aff 0x0
        base 0xffffffff10010000 lim 0x10060000
        (gicrbase 0x0 gicrsize 0x0)
      frame  0 off 0x0      aff 0x0        typer.lo 0x0
      frame  1 off 0x20000  aff 0x0        typer.lo 0x0
      frame  2 off 0x40000  aff 0xffffffff typer.lo 0xffffffff Last PLPIS VLPIS
      ... frame reads all-ones (unmapped); stopping
    ...
    getrregs cpu1 want 0x1: last frame aff 0xffffffff typer 0xffffffff
    panic: getrregs: no re-distributor for cpu 1 (aff 0x1)

Read it carefully -- THREE facts, all decisive:

  (a) Both frame 0 AND frame 1 report aff 0x0, typer.lo 0x0.  A
      real GICR_TYPER mirrors MPIDR affinity in [63:32] and carries
      Processor_Number/Last/VLPIS in the low word; ALL of those read
      back as ZERO here.  So affinity matching (Bug 7) can NEVER
      distinguish cpu1 -- nothing in the GIC reports aff 1.  cpu0
      "worked" only because want==0 accidentally equals the zeroed
      field.  Matching by Processor_Number (the original code) and
      matching by Last (7b/7d) are equally dead: both fields are 0.

  (b) The two MAPPED frames are at 0x0 and 0x20000; 0x40000 reads
      all-ones (unmapped).  So the layout is exactly 2 cpus x
      0x20000 stride = a 0x40000 region.  frame0=cpu0, frame1=cpu1,
      positionally, in cpu order.  (Note frame2's all-ones happens
      to set bits that DECODE as Last+PLPIS+VLPIS -- a red herring
      that fed the 7b VLPI-stride theory.  It is just 0xffffffff.)

  (c) gicrbase 0x0 gicrsize 0x0 -- the DTB intc-node parse FAILED,
      so 7d's "bound the walk by the DTB region" never engaged and
      the walk used the compiled-in fallback.  The node name did
      not match "/intc" or "/interrupt-controller".

Two-part fix this session:

  1. gic.c getrregs: keep affinity match as the PREFERRED path
     (real hw / qemu), but require aff != 0 for it to count (so the
     all-zero VZ field never false-matches cpu0), and add a
     POSITIONAL FALLBACK: cpu N uses the Nth redistributor frame.
     getrregs is only ever called for the running cpu, so the index
     is just machno.  Stride is GICRFRAME (0x20000) unless the DTB
     gave a gicrsize that divides evenly by conf.nmach, in which
     case gicrsize/nmach is the authoritative per-cpu stride (the
     guest-visible analogue of Apple's
     hv_gic_get_redistributor_size: total region / ncpu -- this is
     what disambiguates a plain-GICv3 0x20000 from a GICv4/VLPI
     0x40000 layout WITHOUT guessing from VLPIS, which 7d proved
     unreliable).  The fallback verifies the chosen frame is mapped
     (not all-ones) before returning it.

  2. bootargs.c: fix the GIC-node match so gicrbase/gicrsize
     actually get populated.  Stop trusting the node NAME; latch
     onto the node whose `compatible` property contains "gic-v3"
     (memhas() substring scan over the NUL-separated list), record
     its path, and capture that node's `reg`.  Name heuristics
     (/intc, /interrupt-controller, /gic) remain only as a fallback
     when no compatible match was seen.  bootargsinit() now PRINTS
     the captured gic node path, gicd/gicr base+size, and the
     derived per-cpu stride, so the next boot says outright whether
     the DTB parse finally worked and what the real region size is.

WHY THIS SHOULD WORK where 7/7b/7d did not: it stops trying to read
identity out of a TYPER that VZ zeroes, and instead uses the one
thing the dump PROVED is true -- redistributors are laid out one
per cpu, in order, 0x20000 apart, terminated by unmapped space.

VERIFIED -- 2-cpu boot (9vz default -cpus 2) reaches the rc prompt
with cpu1 online.  cpu1 passes getrregs via the positional fallback
(frame 1), does the 7c GICR_WAKER wake, and continues through
clockinit/synccycles/timersinit/mmu1init/schedinit to the
scheduler.  The "SMP: DONE" milestone at the top of this file is
the authoritative status.

Bug 7f: make the SECONDARY path and the BARRIER talk (THIS SESSION)
-------------------------------------------------------------------
Observation that drove this: we were "posting literally everything
from the console" and STILL guessing, because the secondary cpu's
path is silent by construction and the cross-cpu barrier hangs
mutely.  Two specific blind spots, both now scribbled over:

(1) main.c secondary heartbeat.  The `if(m->machno)` block in
    main() ran trapinit/fpuinit/intrinit/clockinit/synccycles/
    timersinit/mmu1init/schedinit with NO output.  If cpu1 wedges
    or faults in any of them, the console shows nothing past
    whatever cpu0 last printed.  With *smpdebug set each stage now
    prints
        cpuN main: <stage>
    BEFORE running it, so the LAST such line names the stage that
    hung.  (iprint = polling putc, does not need this cpu's clock
    or scheduler.)  cpuidprint()'s "cpuN: Apple Virtualization.
    framework" (always printed, no switch) is the success marker
    that the secondary got past clockinit; reaching it on every
    secondary means SMP is up.  (Gated behind *smpdebug now that
    SMP works -- see the diagnostics block at the top.)

(2) clock.c synccycles() barrier.  HISTORICAL SILENT-HANG TRAP:
    synccycles is a spin barrier (every cpu waits until
    r->ref == conf.nmach).  It is called by cpu0 at the END of
    mpinit and by every secondary in main().  If ANY cpu dies
    (panics/exits) before reaching its synccycles -- exactly what
    the getrregs panic did, "cpu1: exiting" -- the survivors spin
    here FOREVER with no output.  That is the canonical "SMP boot
    just hangs with nothing on screen."  Fixed: the spins are now
    in syncwait(), which after a huge spin count prints
        synccycles: cpuN stuck at <enter|leave> barrier:
                    have M of K cpus
    then keeps waiting (and will reprint).  So a stuck barrier now
    SAYS which cpu is stuck and how many it is missing: "have 1 of
    2" from cpu0 means a secondary never arrived; from a secondary
    it means cpu0 never released it.

These are diagnosis aids, not fixes; they turn a mute hang into a
labelled one.  Single-cpu boots: heartbeat block is m->machno-
gated (never runs on cpu0), syncwait's threshold is never reached
when conf.nmach==1 (r->ref hits 1 immediately).  No behaviour
change for the working terminal/cpu boot.

Panic-from-secondary note: panic/dumpstack use iprint -> putc desc
0 (polling) under the uartvz txl ilock, and dumpstackwithureg
delay(2000)s after the ktrace line, so a secondary's last words DO
drain before it exits -- we saw this work already (the original
getrregs panic text arrived intact).  If a future secondary panic
produces TRUNCATED output, suspect the txl ilock contending with
cpu0 or the virtio backend stalling during teardown; *nodumpstack
(getconf) skips the stack walk to shorten the window.

WHAT A HEALTHY SMP BOOT LOOKS LIKE with *gicdebug AND *smpdebug set
(without them, only the "cpu1: Apple Virtualization.framework" line
appears -- the rest is silenced; see the "SMP diagnostics" block at
the top):
    ... cpu0 boot through chandevreset ...
    dumprregs: cpu0 ... (the redistributor map)
      frame ...
    ... mpinit: CPU_ON cpu1 mpid ... ...
    cpu1 main: trapinit
    cpu1 main: fpuinit
    cpu1 main: intrinit
    (cpu1's own dumprregs only appears here if getrregs PANICS)
    cpu1 main: clockinit
    cpu1: Apple Virtualization.framework
    cpu1 main: synccycles
    cpu1 main: timersinit
    cpu1 main: mmu1init
    (cpu1 then enters schedinit and joins the scheduler)
Anything missing from the tail of that list = the next thing to
look at.  A "synccycles: cpuN stuck ... have M of K" line = a cpu
died before the barrier; read upward for its last heartbeat/panic.

